All,

I&#39;m digging through old mails, and wanted to provide some closure on 
this issue.  In the end, we went with the specification:

    /**
     * Optionally specify &lt;code&gt;expected&lt;/code&gt;, a Throwable, to cause a 
test method to succeed iff
     * an exception of the specified class is thrown by the method.
     */
    Class&lt;? extends Throwable&gt; expected() default None.class;

Speaking only for myself, the most convincing reason to do this is that 
it hews closest to the idiom that would most often be used by JUnit 3 users:

try {
    doSomethingRisky();
    fail();
} catch (ExceptionSuperclass e) {
    // success!
}

Before the new implementation was in place, moving some old test 
definitions from JUnit 3 to JUnit 4, this bit me: I couldn&#39;t just 
transfer the class name from the catch clause to the &quot;expected&quot; 
attribute, because sometimes the actually thrown exceptions were 
subclasses of the caught exceptions.

You may feel that the old idiom was too loose--in that case, sadly, the 
new attribute will also be too loose for you.  That&#39;s consistency for 
you, I guess.  The extension support should allow you do define your own 
ThrowsExactException attribute, if you wish, or you can do an explicit 
catch.

Thanks,

    David Saff

Kent Beck wrote:
&gt; Ben,
&gt;
&gt; Thank you for the feedback. We went around on this. It seems there are two
&gt; cases:
&gt;
&gt; 1) I am throwing an exception but I want to make it more specific so I 
&gt; throw
&gt; a subclass (Exception -&gt; IllegalArgumentException). No catch clauses care
&gt; about the more-specific exception. If expected is looking for a precise
&gt; class, a bunch of tests will break even though the code still works.
&gt;
&gt; 2) The scenario you introduced--there are catch clauses in place that are
&gt; looking for the more-specific exception. If expected is looking for any
&gt; subclass of an exception class, the code might not work any more but the
&gt; tests would pass.
&gt;
&gt; Either way you&#39;re going to get false results. One question is which 
&gt; scenario
&gt; is more common? Another is which scenario is more 
&gt; dangerous/risky/expensive?
&gt;
&gt; Take care,
&gt;
&gt; Kent Beck
&gt; Three Rivers Institute
&gt;
